Is it? The only information I could find on Wackypedia was that it was petroleum-derived.

isopropylbenzene from petroleum --> oxidized to cumene hydroperoxide under controlled conditions --> one byproduct of cumene hydroperoxide manufacture is acetophenone --> reacts with ethyl monochloroacetate under alkaline conditions (the Darzens condensation) to produce ethyl methylphenylglycidate, which is a key ingredient in lots of artificial fruit flavors, including but not limited to artificial strawberry flavoring. The artificial strawberry flavoring sold in the food service industry is typically a blend of 40-50 or more individual chemicals, normally dissolved in water at a standardized concentration for ease of measurement and handling.

Castor oil might be less off-putting than this.

Artificial vanilla flavoring is pretty good. It is very difficult to distinguish it from real vanilla extract. Fruit flavors thus far have been much harder to reproduce economically, and you have probably already noticed that, for example, grape soda doesn't really taste like grapes. Maybe some day.
